message: The introductory paragraph was changed to more accurately reflect the historical context of New Mexico
Corrected New Mexico Territory....problem is that period is in the 19th century and Genizaros thrived in the previous century.
added "including" for the sake of clarity
Nuevo Mexico to New Mexico.  For the sake of continuity and clarity
Sheep herders is most commonly used in the vernacular of New Mexico among many Genizaro descendants.

Removed language that interfered with clarity.  Hispano is not acceptable to Genizaro descendants who prefer the term indigenous or Chicano. The contestation over contemporary terminology makes it best to simply state the facts clearly
Redundant, Carnue is already mentioned in the previous sentence
Hispano is a contemporary term that was not employed during the Spanish and Mexican periods.
Deleted the term hispanos from first sentence.   The term was not in use during the dime period but is a contemporary term.   The edition makes clear that the slaves were Native Americans.
Clarified point that Comanches kidnapped the children they sold.
Santa Fe Revolt to Chimayoso Revolt.  It is known as the Chimayoso Revolt not the Santa Fe Revolt.
Added more pertinent information about descendents today.
Made opening paragraph more clear and succinct.
Added information on the use of the term Genizaro in New Mexico.
Added a more detailed explanation of the information from Brugge for the purpose of providing greater clarity.

Corrected the title of Estevan Rael Galvez dissertation.  Title is: "Identifying and Capturing Identity: Narratives of American Indian Servitude, Colorado and New Mexico, 1750-1930." Ph.D. diss., University of Michigan, 2002.
/* 19th Century */ Pueblo tribes was changed to Pueblo Indians/Natives to more accurately reflect the contemporary identification of Pueblo peoples today and historically.
Added clarification of the word "coyote" which was actually used to describe the children and grandchildren of Genizaros.
/* History */ Moved a sentance to avoid repetition and provided clarity.
Cleaned  up a the section and added a reference.
/* Etymology */ Provided further clarification of the usage of the word Genizaro in the Northern frontier of the Spanish Empire in America and provided reference sources.
I provided a footnote reference for the quotation about settlement of Genizaros.
I inserted information that contributes to the acccuracy of the page.
I have inserted a quote which adds to the accuracy of the page.  Moreover, I have inserted Mixed Blood Indians rather that "tribal Members"  Genizaros were not tribal members.
/* 19th Century */ this canve was made to provide accuracy.  Genizaros were not and are not tribal ~~~~members.

Indian is used more widely in New Mexico thant any other term except perhaps indigenous terms such as "Dine" to refer to a particiluar group.
